# Testing Norms

## Context

- When modifying existing code or specifications
- When adding new functionality or features
- When refactoring or restructuring code

## Requirements

- Run existing tests after any code modification
- Create unit tests for all new functionality
- Consult user if tests fail after modifications
- Ensure test coverage for changed code paths
- **Testing stack consistency**: use **Vitest** for unit/functional tests across frontend and backend.
- **File co-location**: every source file must be accompanied by a spec file in the same folder.
  - Source: `foo.ts`
  - Unit/functional spec: `foo.spec.ts`
  - Integration spec (DB/Docker/network): `foo.integration.spec.ts` (still co-located)
- **Backend route testing**: prefer **Fastify `app.inject()`** for HTTP/route tests (no real ports, stable and fast).
- **Integration tests**:
  - Keep them co-located but separated by suffix (`*.integration.spec.ts`).
  - Provide separate scripts so unit tests can run quickly by default and integration tests can be run explicitly.
- **Coverage**:
  - Enable coverage reporting in test configuration.
  - Backend (API) coverage must be **>= 95%** (lines, statements, functions, branches) and should fail the test run if thresholds are not met.
- **Environment**:
  - Respect the repo convention that environment variables live at the **repo root** (e.g. root `.env` / `.env.test` patterns), not per-package `.env` files.
- **Insomnia (manual API / smoke requests)**:
  - When **adding** or **modifying** HTTP API routes under `services/api`, **update** `insomnia/collections/badgers-api.yaml` in the **same task** (or immediately after) so the repo stays the source of truth for manual testing.
  - Add or adjust the matching folder, request (`method`, `url`, `body`, `headers`), **`settings.cookies`** for session routes, and **`scripts.afterResponse`** checks for success and response shape.
  - Follow **`.cursor/rules/1002-insomnia-auto.mdc`** for YAML structure, env keys, and script style.
  - Keep **`insomnia/README.md`** in sync when import paths or variables change.

## Examples

<example>
Good: After adding a new API endpoint, run existing API tests and create unit tests for the new endpoint functionality
</example>

<example>
Good: Add `services/api/src/modules/health/health-routes.spec.ts` next to `health-routes.ts` and test routes using `app.inject()`. Add `health-routes.integration.spec.ts` only if it truly needs a live database.
</example>

<example>
Good: Enforce API coverage by configuring thresholds to >=95% and running coverage in CI.
</example>

<example>
Good: After adding `PATCH /assets/:id`, extend Vitest route tests with `app.inject()` and add or update the Insomnia request in `insomnia/collections/badgers-api.yaml` with body, cookies, and after-response assertions.
</example>

<example type="invalid">
Bad: Adding new features without creating corresponding unit tests or running existing test suite
</example>

<example type="invalid">
Bad: Putting unit tests in a separate `tests/` folder that breaks the one-source-one-spec co-location convention.
</example>

<example type="invalid">
Bad: Using Supertest against a real port for basic route tests when `app.inject()` is sufficient.
</example>

## Critical Points

<critical>
  - ALWAYS run tests after code modifications
  - ALWAYS create unit tests for new functionality
  - ALWAYS consult user if tests fail
  - ENSURE test coverage matches code changes
  - ALWAYS use Vitest and co-located `*.spec.ts` / `*.integration.spec.ts`
  - ENFORCE backend coverage >= 95%
  - ALWAYS update Insomnia `insomnia/collections/badgers-api.yaml` when public REST routes are added or changed (per `1002-insomnia-auto.mdc`)
</critical>
